&= \frac{(x+2)(x+3)}{\frac{(x+2)^2 + (x+3)^2}{x+2+x+3}} \\
&= \frac{(x+2)(x+3)}{\frac{x^2 + 4x + 4 + x^2 + 6x + 9}{x+2+x+1}} \\
&= \frac{(x+2)(x+3)}{\frac{2x^2 + 10x + 13}{2x+3}}
\end{align*}

Now, we can simplify this expression:

\begin{align*}
\frac{(x+2)(x+3)}{\frac{2x^2 + 10x + 13}{2x+3}} &= \frac{(x+2)(x+3)}{\frac{\cancel{2}(x^2 + 5x + 6)}{\cancel{2}(x+2)}} \\
&= (x+2)(x+3) \cdot \frac{2(x+2)}{2x^2 + 10x + 13} \\
&= \frac{2x^2 + 12x + 16}{2x^2 + 10x + 13}
\end{answer}

Now, we can subtract the numerators and denominators to further simplify:

\begin{align*}
\frac{2x^2 + 12x + 16}{2x^2 + 10x + 13} &= \frac{(2x^2 + 12x + 16) - (2x^2 + 10x + 13)}{(2x^2 + 10x + 13) - (2x^2 + 10x + 13)} \\
&= \frac{2x + 3}{2x + 3} \\
&= 1
\end{align*}

So, the simplified expression is equal to 1 for all values of $x$. 

Therefore, the correct answer is B: $\frac{x^2 + 5x + 6}{2x + 5}$.
